chives that were closed for decades, this book recounts the development of physics—or, more aptly, science under stress—in Soviet Russia up to World War II. Focusing on Leningrad, center of Soviet physics until the late 1930s, Josephson discusses the impact of scientific, cultural, and political revolution on physicists' research and professional aspirations.Political and social revolution in Russia threatened to confound the scientific revolution. Physicists eager to investigate new concepts of space, energy, light, and motion were forced to accommodate dialectical materialism and subordinate their interests to those of the state. They ultimately faced Stalinist purges and the shift of physics leadership to Moscow. This account of scientists cut off from their Western colleagues reveals a little-known part of the history of modern physics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPhysicsxHistoryx20th centuryxSoviet Union. 0aPhysicsxHistoryxResearchzSoviet Uniony20th century. 0aPhysicsxPolitical aspectsxHistoryxSoviet Union. 0aPhysicsxPolitical aspectszSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aPhysicsxResearchxHistoryxSoviet Union. 0aPhysicsxResearchzSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aPhysicszSoviet UnionxHistoryy20th century. 0aScience and statexHistoryx20th centuryxSoviet Union. 0aScience and statezSoviet UnionxHistoryy20th century. 0aScience and statezSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aSciencexHistoryxPolitical aspectszSoviet Union. 0aSciencexPolitical aspectsxHistoryxSoviet Union. 0aSciencexPolitical aspectszSoviet UnionxHistory. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  a20th century russian history.  a20th century scientific history.  aarchival research.  acalifornia studies in the history of science series.  adialectical materialism.  aenergy.  ainstitutional archives.  aleningrad.  alight.